        <title><m>\S 2.2</m>: Matrix Multiplication and Linear Systems</title>
            <page>
                <exercise workspace="2in">
                    <title>Motivation: Matrix Multiplication and Linear Systems</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
					<solution>
						<p>
							Last time we made sense of <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m> in terms of linear combinations
							of column vectors with specific weights to get a new vector. Recall also that the
							"membership" question is important. We'll rephrase and answer this question
							in this new context.
						</p>
					</solution>
                    
                </exercise>
                <exercise workspace="5in">
                    <title>Membership: Three Perspectives</title>
                    <statement>
                        <p>
                            
                        </p>
                    </statement>
                    <solution>
						<p>
							The following questions are all equivalent:
							<ol>
								<li>
									<p>
										For an <m>m \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m> and vector <m>\bvec \in \R^m</m>, 
										does there exist a vector <m>\xvec \in \R^n</m> such that <m>A\xvec = \bvec</m>?
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										Are there weights <m>c_1, \dots, c_n</m> such that <m>c_1\vvec_1 + \dots + c_n\vvec_n = \bvec</m>?
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										Does the system represented by <m>[\vvec_1 \dots \vvec_n | \bvec]</m> have a solution?
									</p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
						<p>
						This is also summarized in <url href="https://understandinglinearalgebra.org/sec-matrices-lin-combs.html#prop-matrix-eq-solution">Proposition 2.2.4</url>.
						</p>
					</solution>
                    
                </exercise>
            </page>

